HEADWORD: Dolerite
<hw>Dol"er*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr.
<grk>dolero`s</grk> deceptive, because it was easily confounded with
diorite.]</ety> <fld>(Petrography)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A dark,
crystalline, igneous rock, chiefly pyroxene with labradorite.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>Coarse-grained basalt.</def> <sd>(c)</sd>
<def>Diabase.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>Any dark, igneous rock composed
chiefly of silicates of iron and magnesium with some feldspar.</def> --
<wordforms><wf>Dol`er*it"ic</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Doleritic</ent>⟦br⟧
